BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Charge transport in organic semiconductors\n\nOrganic semicondu
 ctors have a range of applications\, including flexible electronics and\nsp
 ectrum-optimized photovoltaics. However\, applications of these materials h
 ave been\nconstrained by low device efficiencies and an incomplete understa
 nding of their intricate\ncharge transport mechanisms. Traditional current-
 voltage transfer curve analysis is a\nbulk method and can lead to unreliabl
 e parameter measurements when faced with non-\nideal circumstances such as 
 contact resistance. In our work\, we use modulated\namplitude reflectance s
 pectroscopy (MARS) amplitude measurements to obtain high-\nresolution\, two
 -dimensional maps of the carrier distribution in the channel of an organic\
 nfield effect transistor under varying bias conditions. MARS phase images p
 rovide\nspatially resolved maps of charge carrier transport dynamics in the
  transistor channel\nand enable quantitative measurement of the drift veloc
 ity under operating conditions. By\nenabling spatially-resolved characteriz
 ation of both charge carrier distribution and\ntransport dynamics in an act
 ively biased transistor\, MARS imaging allows us to begin to\nexplore the r
 elationship between material structure and charge transport in organic\nsem
 iconductors.\n\nI am the Seeley W Mudd Professor of Physics at Pomona Colle
 ge\, and I love working\nwith students in the classroom and research lab. I
  teach a wide range of courses\,\nincluding Big Ideas in Physics\, Modern P
 hysics\, Electronics\, Research Methods\, and\nlab courses. My research int
 erests are largely in the area of sustainability\, working on\nnext generat
 ion photovoltaics\, passive radiative cooling\, and more. Outside of work\,
  I\nlove to hike\, camp\, backpack\, kayak\, bike\, ski\, and travel.\nI di
 d my undergraduate work at Swarthmore College\, earning a B.A. in mathemati
 cs and\na B.S. in engineering. After that\, I studied at the University of 
 Oxford as a Rhodes\nScholar\, earning an M.Sc. in “maths\,” in addition to 
 rowing crew and traveling the world.\nI earned my Ph.D. in electrical engin
 eering from U.C. Berkeley. I then joined the\nphysics department at Mount H
 olyoke College\, where I served as a professor\,\ndepartment chair\, and as
 sociate dean and also founded a startup company Alenas\nImaging based on my
  research. In 2013\, I moved to Pomona College\, serving as the\nDean of th
 e College and Vice President for Academic Affairs. I am now happily back to
 \nbeing a full-time faculty member\, which is my favorite job of all!
DTEND:20260219T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260314T021911Z
DTSTART:20260219T003000Z
GEO:45.480964;-122.630146
LOCATION:Physics\, 123
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Physics Seminar with Janice Hudgings
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52066895428857
URL:https://events.reed.edu/event/physics-seminar-with-janice-hudgings
END:VEVENT
