BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Imaging almost nothing at all … with an instrument the size of 
 a planet (the PUNCH mission)\n\nWe are bathed in the Sun’s outer atmosphere
 .  The outer solar corona is not gravitationally confined\, and escapes con
 tinuously to fill the solar system with a supersonic\, if very tenuous\, fl
 uid called the “solar wind”.  The solar wind is a hot plasma: an electrical
 ly neutral mixture of ions and free electrons.  The electrons scatter sunli
 ght\, rendering the corona and the solar wind visible in principle (though 
 they are too faint to see under normal conditions on Earth).  The solar win
 d forms streams\, eddies\, clouds\, and other hydrodynamic structures as it
  flows through the void between planets.  I will describe the amazing physi
 cs behind this ethereal material\, which washes over everything in the sola
 r system — including Earth.  I’ll also describe PUNCH\, a NASA mission to i
 mage the corona and solar wind as parts of a single\, unified system.  With
  PUNCH we hope to better understand solar astrophysics\, space weather\, an
 d space plasmas in general – by making this invisible world... visible.\n\n
 Dr. Craig DeForest (Reed College ’89) has a very long history of causing tr
 ouble for Johnny Powell.  His time at Reed was marked by way too many trips
  to the Ski Cabin\, freak hailstorms\, the explosion of the Space Shuttle\,
  an appearance of Halley’s Comet\, the failure of the Reed Out Of Africa di
 vestiture movement\, and the dismantling of the Berlin Wall – some of which
  may not have been DeForest’s fault.  He lived in the now-defunct TVS Reed 
 House\, did his thesis work under a very young Mary James\, and went on to 
 Ph.D. studies at Stanford University in the early 1990s.  He has been invol
 ved in every major NASA solar observing mission since 1995\, pioneering man
 y image analysis techniques in common use today in the solar physics commun
 ity.  He currently directs a department of 25 scientists at the Southwest R
 esearch Institute\, in Boulder\, Colorado\, and leads NASA’s PUNCH mission 
 to image the solar wind throughout the inner solar system.
DTEND:20260226T013000Z
DTSTAMP:20260314T021911Z
DTSTART:20260226T003000Z
GEO:45.480964;-122.630146
LOCATION:Physics\, 123
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Physics Seminar with Craig DeForest
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52128408999102
URL:https://events.reed.edu/event/physics-seminar-with-craig-deforest
END:VEVENT
