BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture
DESCRIPTION:Trust Nothing!  Object lessons in science\, through the lens of
  real image analysis\n\nScientific images are powerful tools to understand 
 the world around us.  Image processing is a major part of many fields\, esp
 ecially solar physics (which studies the only well-resolved star).  But ext
 racting good science from images is fraught with peril\, because even “stra
 ightforward” analyses contain hidden traps.  I’ll present some cautionary t
 ales culled from a career spent staring at way too much solar data\, coveri
 ng five topics.  (a) Collection: you don’t understand your instrument. (b) 
 Interpretation: your eyes lie to you. (c) Data preparation: you’re probably
  doing it wrong.  (d) Image display: you’re likely screwing that up too.  (
 e) There’s hope: don’t trust\, verify.  The take-away lesson: channel your 
 inner Karl Popper\, and think about what exactly your instrument can (or ca
 n’t) tell you\, in the form of falsifying models of the world.  Even someth
 ing as simple as a movie can deceive the unwary\; the defense is to be wary
  of everything.\n\nDr. Craig DeForest (Reed College ’89) has a very long hi
 story of causing trouble for Johnny Powell.  His time at Reed was marked by
  way too many trips to the Ski Cabin\, freak hailstorms\, the explosion of 
 the Space Shuttle\, an appearance of Halley’s Comet\, the failure of the Re
 ed Out Of Africa divestiture movement\, and the dismantling of the Berlin W
 all – some of which may not have been DeForest’s fault.  He lived in the no
 w-defunct TVS Reed House\, did his thesis work under a very young Mary Jame
 s\, and went on to Ph.D. studies at Stanford University in the early 1990s.
   He has been involved in every major NASA solar observing mission since 19
 95\, pioneering many image analysis techniques in common use today in the s
 olar physics community.  He currently directs a department of 25 scientists
  at the Southwest Research Institute\, in Boulder\, Colorado\, and leads NA
 SA’s PUNCH mission to image the solar wind throughout the inner solar syste
 m.
DTEND:20260226T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260314T021911Z
DTSTART:20260226T200000Z
GEO:45.480964;-122.630146
LOCATION:Physics\, 123
SEQUENCE:0
